Random Forest¶

Random forest is same as bagging , but we have a very small difference¶

We follow the following steps¶

1) Let our Dataset be D , having 'd' number of features¶

2) Next we create a bootstrap samples from D by resampling with replacement¶

3) Now we grow the decision tree (say Ti) for each bootstrap sample (say Di)¶

4) So in Random forest , at each node of our tree we do not consider all the features for best split , instead we connsider only a subset of feature to create a best split to our tree.¶

5) In our modern Random forest algorithm of growing a tree , we make sure to consider all the features in our tree , by changing the subset features at each nodes. This subset of features are referred to as the Random subspace¶

6) Typically, for a classification problem with p features, √p (rounded down) features are used in each split.For regression problems the inventors recommend p/3 (rounded down) with a minimum node size of 5 as the default.In practice the best values for these parameters will depend on the problem, and they should be treated as tuning parameters¶

What is the benefit of Random Forest over bagging ?¶

The reason for doing this is the correlation of the trees in an ordinary bootstrap sample: if one or a few features are very strong predictors for the response variable (target output), these features will be selected in many of the B trees, causing them to become correlated. To avoid this and to increase our performance ,we consider building trees in amost possible ways ,hence we use the Random forest method¶

So we can say that Random forest helps in avoiding highly correlated trees¶

An interesting point to note is that the averaging highly correlated trees gives a high variance than in decorrelated trees . So as a result we now have an increased perfomance in predictions¶

Result¶

for a given x , take the majority vote of y from all our samples ( in case of Classification )¶

for a given x , take the mean of y from all our samples ( in case of Regression )¶
